<DOC><DOCNO> AP880917-0137 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-17-88 1621EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Hurricane-Glance 1stLd-Writethru   09-17 0266</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hurricane-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0592,0291</SECOND><HEAD>Casualties And Damage From Hurricane Gilbert At A Glance</HEAD><NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd item to UPDATE with 200 feared dead in Monterrey.</NOTE><HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press:</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are reports of casualties and damage causedby Hurricane Gilbert last week:</TEXT><HEAD>TEXAS</HEAD><TEXT>   Dozens of tornadoes spawned by Gilbert hit southern Texas onSaturday, following 14 on Friday. At least two people died Saturday.</TEXT><HEAD>MEXICO</HEAD><TEXT>   In Monterrey, a river surged over its banks Saturday andoverturned four buses, and 200 people were feared dead. The stormearlier left 29 people dead on the Yucatan peninsula.</TEXT><HEAD>JAMAICA</HEAD><TEXT>   At least 26 people have been killed and 500,000 left homeless.The government declared a one-month state of emergency along theeastern coast and imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew to prevent looting.Damage was estimated at $8 billion.</TEXT><HEAD>HAITI</HEAD><TEXT>   At 30 people were killed when Gilbert swept across the southernpeninsula. The military government declared a state of emergency inthe three southern departments, where 50 to 60 percent of theagricultural production was destroyed. A famine was predicted inthat region within two months.</TEXT><HEAD>DOMINICAN REPUBLIC</HEAD><TEXT>   Gilbert caused flooding and widespread crop damage. Damage tothe main electricity relay station blacked out much of SantoDomingo, the capital. Five people were reported dead and 100families homeless.</TEXT><HEAD>HONDURAS</HEAD><TEXT>   Eight people drowned, 6,000 people were homeless and 27,000acres of crops were destroyed.</TEXT><HEAD>CAYMAN ISLANDS</HEAD><TEXT>   Flooding was widespread, with an estimated 5 percent to 10percent of the houses damaged. Electricity and telephone servicewas disrupted.</TEXT></DOC>